STATE OF MICHIGAN
IN THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR THE COUNTY OF MUSKEGON
FAMILY DIVISION

ANDREW PIGORS,
     Plaintiff,
                                                                  Case No.: 24-01507-DC
v.                                                             Hon. Jenny L. McNeill

EMILY WATSON,
     Defendant.
_____________________________________________________________________________/

PROPOSED ORDER GRANTING DISQUALIFICATION OF JUDGE

At a session of said Court held at the
Muskegon County Hall of Justice,
990 Terrace Street, Muskegon, Michigan
on _____________, 2026

PRESENT: HONORABLE ___________________________
           Chief Judge, Muskegon County Circuit Court

This matter came before the Court on Plaintiff Andrew Pigors' Motion for Disqualification of Judge pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(1).

THE COURT FINDS:

1. This Court has jurisdiction over this Motion pursuant to MCR 2.003(C) and MCR 2.003(D)(1).

2. The Motion is accompanied by an Affidavit of Disqualification setting forth specific facts as required by MCR 2.003(C)(2).

3. The Motion was timely filed within fourteen (14) days of Plaintiff discovering the factual basis for disqualification.

4. The Motion is filed in good faith and is not a dilatory tactic.

5. Plaintiff has established grounds for disqualification under MCR 2.003(C)(1) based on the following findings:

   A. PATTERN OF EX PARTE ORDERS

   The record demonstrates that Judge Jenny L. McNeill has entered twenty-four (24) ex parte orders affecting Plaintiff's fundamental parental rights without providing notice or opportunity to be heard. These orders represent 43.6% of all orders entered in this case.

   This pattern includes:
   • Five ex parte orders entered on the same day (August 8, 2025)
   • Multiple orders suspending parenting time without notice or hearing
   • Custody modifications entered within 24 hours of filing, without opportunity for Plaintiff to respond
   • Orders based solely on unverified allegations without evidentiary hearings

   B. DISPARATE TREATMENT OF PARTIES

   The statistical evidence demonstrates systematic disparate treatment:
   • Defendant's motions granted 83% of time vs. Plaintiff's motions granted 18% of time
   • Average response time to Defendant's motions: 8.3 days vs. Plaintiff's motions: 47.6 days
   • Defendant's motions for reconsideration: 100% granted with hearings vs. Plaintiff's: 0% granted
   • Substantively identical motions receiving opposite results based on party identity

   C. APPEARANCE OF IMPROPRIETY

   A person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality based on:
   • 44% ex parte order rate
   • Significant statistical disparities in treatment of parties
   • Five orders entered on same day without notice
   • Pattern of accepting one party's allegations without proof while rejecting other party's evidence
   • Credibility determinations made against Plaintiff without evidentiary hearings

   D. CANON VIOLATIONS

   Judge McNeill's conduct violates multiple Canons of Judicial Conduct:
   • Canon 2: Creates appearance of impropriety through pattern of disparate treatment
   • Canon 3(B)(7): Twenty-four documented violations of prohibition on ex parte communications
   • Canon 3(B)(8): Systematic disparity in response times denies equal treatment

   E. DUE PROCESS VIOLATIONS

   Judge McNeill's ex parte orders violate:
   • MCR 2.119(E): Notice requirements for motions
   • MCR 3.207: Notice requirements for custody and parenting time orders
   • Fourteenth Amendment: Due process before deprivation of fundamental parental rights
   • Michigan Constitution Article 1, § 17: Due process guarantee

6. The cumulative pattern of conduct establishes both actual bias under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(a) and appearance of impropriety under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b).

7. Disqualification is necessary to:
   • Protect Plaintiff's right to an impartial tribunal
   • Preserve public confidence in the integrity of the judicial system
   • Ensure fair and equal treatment of both parties
   • Safeguard the best interests of the minor child
   • Prevent further constitutional violations

8. Reassignment to another judge is necessary to remedy the due process violations and ensure fair proceedings going forward.

9. Given the procedural irregularities documented in the record, Plaintiff should have opportunity to raise appropriate motions before the newly assigned judge.

IT IS HEREBY ORDERED:

1. Plaintiff's Motion for Disqualification of Judge is GRANTED.

2. The Honorable Jenny L. McNeill is DISQUALIFIED from further presiding over Case No. 24-01507-DC, Pigors v. Watson.

3. This case is REASSIGNED to another judge of the Muskegon County Circuit Court, Family Division, to be designated by the Chief Judge.

4. The newly assigned judge shall schedule a status conference within thirty (30) days of this Order to:
   a. Review the procedural history of the case
   b. Address any orders that should be reconsidered due to lack of proper notice or hearing
   c. Establish procedures for fair and equal treatment of both parties going forward
   d. Address any other matters appropriate for ensuring fair proceedings

5. Plaintiff's rights to file appropriate motions for reconsideration of orders entered without proper notice or hearing are PRESERVED.

6. All previous orders in this case shall remain in effect pending review by the newly assigned judge, except that:
   a. Both parties may file motions to reconsider any order that was entered without proper notice
   b. The newly assigned judge shall give such motions expedited consideration
   c. Any party may request emergency relief if circumstances warrant

7. This Order shall be effective immediately upon entry.

8. The Clerk of the Court is directed to:
   a. Remove Judge Jenny L. McNeill from the assignment in Case No. 24-01507-DC
   b. Reassign the case to a judge designated by the Chief Judge
   c. Notify all parties of the reassignment
   d. Transmit the complete court file to the newly assigned judge

9. The newly assigned judge shall not be bound by any rulings, findings, or determinations made by Judge McNeill that were entered without proper notice or hearing, and may reconsider such matters upon appropriate motion.

10. Costs of this Motion are not awarded to either party.

IT IS SO ORDERED.

